Exercise 0: Introduction to R

This exercise will introduce you to the basic options of R and Rstudio. We will use a data set of the growth of children after renal transplantation (GRRTX.SAV). We will explore this data using several procedures.

Starting Rstudio:
Rstudio is an integrated development environment of R. Rstudio allows you to run R, manage your R scripts and datasets and view created plots. When you start Rstudio, R is started with it.
To start RStudio just double click at the icon:

First we will learn you how to give basic commands in R:

  1. Click on the File menu, choose new file, then R script.

  2. Within the R script, enter the following sum: 5 + 8

  3. To run this code set the cursor to the right of the 8 and press ctrl + enter or click on the Run icon in the upper right corner of the script window. You can also enter commands directly into the Console window below the script. Within Console you only need to press enter. Both the script and console use the same variables and datasets, which all are visible within the environment window on the upper right side of the screen.

a. Installing packages

R works with packages. Packages contain specific functions which extend the functionallity of the program. These packages should be downloaded once, when required. Before we can start, we need to download some packages.

Copy the code and run the script. install.packages(c("car", "DescTools", "dplyr","epitools", "foreign", "ggplot2", "Hmisc", "kableExtra", "knitr", "mvtnorm", "openxlsx", "rio", "rms", "samplesizeCMH", "survival", "survminer"), dependencies = TRUE) # install all packages needed for the assignments and allow R to install the packages that are required for the packages (dependencies = TRUE)

This will install all the package we need during the assignements for CC02. To actually use the package in Rstudio, type and run for example library(rms). Installation has to be done just once, but the library() command has to be run each time you start working with a script, to load the external packages whose functions are used in that script.

Code

library(rms) # load package

Output

After a successful install, you should get the message:
package 'rms' successfully unpacked and MD5 sums checked

b. Loading and inspecting a dataset

When you load a dataset, you should give it an appropriate (easy) name. There are several ways of loading a dataset in R. In order to load .SAV files, we use the function read.spss() from a package called foreign.

Type for example: mydata <- read.spss('namedataset.sav', to.data.frame = TRUE). The to.data.frame parameter of the read.spss() function influences how the function works. You do not need to understand what this parameter does at this moment. This code requires that the .sav file is saved in the same folder. In our case we can a folder with all the data files. By adding ./data you tell R to go to the folder with the data. This gives us the following R code mydata <- read.spss('./data/namedataset.sav', to.data.frame = TRUE).
You can inspect the dataset by running head(Grrtx), or by clicking on the name of the dataset in the top right window under Environment. How many cases does this dataset contain?

Hints

You can search for more information on read.spss() by typing ?read.spss

Code

library(foreign)  # load package

Grrtx <- read.spss('./data/GRRTX.SAV', to.data.frame = TRUE) # load dataset

Output

Grrtx <- read.spss('./data/GRRTX.SAV', to.data.frame = TRUE)

Discussion

Variable lables can be seen by clicking on the name of the dataset in the top right Environment window. When you type the $ sign immediately behind the dataset, R tends to show the available variables autmatically.

This dataset contains 52 cases (observations).

d. Creating basic tables and graphs

For basic tables, R has a function called table(). You can find percentages of table rows and collumns for a table by using prop.table().
Using these functions to discover how many boys had urinary tract abnormalities as diagnosis. What percentage of all boys is that?

Basic R also has convenient functions to create plots. More advanced plots can be created with the packages ggplot2 or lattice, but for now the basic functions suffice:

  1. Create a histogram of age with the function hist()
  2. Use the function boxplot() to create a boxplot of final height stratified by sex.
  3. Use the function plot() to create a scatterplot of final height by target height

Hints

  1. prop.table() shows cell percentages. With 1 as the second argument, it shows row percentages, and with 2 it returns column percentages. For example: prop.table(my_table, 2)
  2. create a table with the function table(), and store that as Table.1 in order to it later in prop.table().
  3. The first argument for the function boxplot has the structure y~grouping variable.
  4. In all basic plotting functions, the argument main can be used to set a title, and xlab and ylab can be used to set axis labels.

Code

Grrtx <- read.spss('./data/GRRTX.SAV', to.data.frame = TRUE) # load dataset

table(Grrtx$SEX, Grrtx$TXNUM) # create the table

# show row percentages
Table.1 <- table(Grrtx$SEX, Grrtx$DIAGN)
prop.table(Table.1, 1)

# create a histogram of age
hist(Grrtx$AGETX, main = "Age at transplant", xlab = "Age", col = "green")

# create a boxplot

plot(Grrtx$TARHT, Grrtx$FINALHT, main = "Target height vs. final height", xlab = "Target height (cm)", ylab = "Final height (cm)", col = "green4", cex = 2, lwd = 2)

e. Computing new variables

We will now create a new variable with the name Difhtsds. This variable is the difference between HTSDSTX and HTSDSHD.

  1. Type: Grrtx$Difhtsds <- Grrtx$HTSDSTX - Grrtx$HTSDSHD
  2. What is the mean of the new variable?
  3. Produce a histogram of the new variable.
  4. Create a new variable Lndurhd wich is the natural logarithm of DURHD.

It is also possible to do a transformation for only a subgroup of cases:

  1. Type: Grrtx$Finalsds[Grrtx$SEX =="M"] <- (Grrtx$FINALHT[Grrtx$SEX =="M"] - 182.0)/6.7
  2. In the same way compute Grrtx$Finalsds for women with the formula: (FINALHT - 168.3)/6.2
  3. Compare the means of FINALHT and Finalsds for both sexes.

Hints

  1. The natural logarithm is created with the function log(): without a second argument, the base of log() is e.
  2. You can run mean() per subgroup using tapply(). See ?tapply for help.

Code

Grrtx <- read.spss('./data/GRRTX.SAV', to.data.frame = TRUE) # load dataset

Grrtx$Difhtsds <- Grrtx$HTSDSTX - Grrtx$HTSDSHD # create new variable Difhtsds

mean(Grrtx$Difhtsds) # calculate the mean

# create a histogram
hist(Grrtx$Difhtsds, main = "Difference in SDS", xlab = "Difference in SDS", col = "orange")
Grrtx$Lndurhd <- log(Grrtx$DURHD) # create Lndurhd

# calculate Finalsds for men and women separately
Grrtx$Finalsds[Grrtx$SEX =="M"] <- (Grrtx$FINALHT[Grrtx$SEX =="M"] - 182.0) / 6.7 
Grrtx$Finalsds[Grrtx$SEX =="F"] <- (Grrtx$FINALHT[Grrtx$SEX =="F"] - 168.3) / 6.2 

# compare the means
tapply(Grrtx$FINALHT, Grrtx$SEX, mean)
tapply(Grrtx$Finalsds, Grrtx$SEX, mean)

Output

tapply() applies a function to each category of a variable.

f. Recoding variables

Sometimes we want to recode a continuous variable into a categorical, or change the categories of a categorical variable. In R, the the procedure is the same for both cases.

We will give two examples:
The variable TXNUM, the number of transplantations, has the values 1, 2 and 3. Now we create a new variable, indicating More than 1 transplantation, i.e.0 = no, 1 = yes:

  1. Grrtx$More1tx[Grrtx$TXNUM == 1] <- 0
  2. Grrtx$More1tx[Grrtx$TXNUM == 2] <- 1
  3. Grrtx$More1tx[Grrtx$TXNUM == 3] <- 1
Run the code, and show how many patients had more than one transplantation.

The variable AGETX, age at first transplantation, ranges from 5 to 15.5. Now we want to categorize age into different groups: lower than 8, between 8 and 12, and older than 12:

  1. Grrtx$Agegr[Grrtx$AGETX < 8] <- 1
  2. Grrtx$Agegr[Grrtx$AGETX > 8 & Grrtx$AGETX < 12] <- 2
  3. Grrtx$Agegr[Grrtx$AGETX > 12] <- 3
Run the code and create an bar plot of this new variable.

Hints

The square brackets [] behind a variable name can be used to specify which subset of the variable is used: [rows,columns].

A bar chart can be made with barplot(). It uses as input the counts per category, which you can create with table(). 

counts <- table(Grrtx$Agegr)

Code

# load dataset
Grrtx <- read.spss('./data/GRRTX.SAV', to.data.frame = TRUE)

# create new variable More1tx
Grrtx$More1tx[Grrtx$TXNUM == 1] <- 0
Grrtx$More1tx[Grrtx$TXNUM == 2] <- 1
Grrtx$More1tx[Grrtx$TXNUM == 3] <- 1

# Show how many patients had more than one translpant
table(Grrtx$More1tx)

# create new variable Agegr
Grrtx$Agegr[Grrtx$AGETX < 8] <- 1
Grrtx$Agegr[Grrtx$AGETX > 8 & Grrtx$AGETX < 12] <- 2
Grrtx$Agegr[Grrtx$AGETX > 12] <- 3

# show barplot of Agegr
counts <- table(Grrtx$Agegr)
barplot(counts, ylab = "Count", xlab = "Age categories", main = "Patients per age category", col = c("green", "orange", "red"))

Output

Question b

The SPSS system file DIET.SAV contains the data of this exercise. Open the data set and inspect the data. Make a new variable containing the difference before - after.
Then calculate the 95% CI for the mean of this veriable, and verify that this is the same as computed in question a.

Hints

Use the mean() and sd() functions to calculate the mean and standard deviation.

Code

library(foreitn) # load library

Diet <- read.spss('./data/DIET.SAV', to.data.frame = TRUE) # load dataset
Diet$diff <- Diet$BEFORE - Diet$AFTER # create new variable

# calculate 95% CI of the mean
n <- length(Diet$diff)  #number of participants
mean <- mean(Diet$diff) 
sd <- sd(Diet$diff)
se <- (1.96 * sd) / sqrt(n)
lower.limit <- mean - se
upper.limit <- mean + se
lower.limit
upper.limit

Output

Exercise 4: Test for mean

Again we use the dataset BLDPRES.SAV.

Question a

Suppose we are interested in the mean of diastolic blood pressure. What is the estimated mean for this rural area in Pakistan? Assume that you know that in your own country the mean diastolic blood pressure is exactly 79.5 mmHg. Is it justified to claim that in this Pakistan area the diastolic blood pressure is higher? To answer this question, perform the one sample t-test to test the null hypothesis that the population mean is 79.5. In R this can be done by performing a t-test with the function t.test(), setting the mu to 79.5.

Hints

The function t.test() needs two arguments: the variable and the mean for comparison. You can find all the arguments of t.test() using ? 

?t.test

Code

# load library
library(foreign)

# load dataset
Bldpres <- read.spss('data/BLDPRES.SAV', to.data.frame = TRUE)

# perform t-test
t.test(Bldpres$dias, mu = 79.5)

Output

t.test(Bldpres$dias, mu = 79.5)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  Bldpres$dias
## t = 2.8883, df = 327, p-value = 0.004132
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 79.5
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  80.01819 82.23181
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##    81.125

Discussion

The output shows that the 95% confidence interval of diastolic blood pressure is between 80 and 82 mmHg. The value of 79.5 mmHg lies outside (below) this interval.

Exercise 5: Comparison of two means

Two means can be compared using the Students two-sample t-test. This test is carried out in R by the function t.test(). The default level of confidence for confidence intervals is 95%, but you can change that setting with the conf.level parameter. For this exercise we again use the data set BLDPRES.

Question a

To investigate the difference in body weight between men and women, carry out a t-test. Is it justified to use the standard t-test which assumes equal standard deviations? What is the P-value and what is your conclusion? What is the 95% confidence interval for the difference in body weight? What is the 99% confidence interval?

Hints

To test if the standard deviations are different in men and women, use the leveneTest() function from the car library. You can read instructions in how to use leveneTest() and t.test() by typing ? in front of it. To test the difference in weight in t.test(), you can specify the formula with a ~ between the variables. 

?t.test

Code

# load libraries
library(foreign)
library(car)

# load dataset
Bldpres <- read.spss('data/BLDPRES.SAV', to.data.frame = TRUE)

# Levene's test
leveneTest(Bldpres$weight ~ Bldpres$sex)

# compare the mean weight between men and women
t.test(Bldpres$weight~Bldpres$sex)

# set the confidence interval to 99%
t.test(Bldpres$weight~Bldpres$sex, conf.level = 0.99)

Output

Question b

Make a new variable, for instance called Highbp, that is equal to 1 if dias is larger than 90, and equal to 0 otherwise. Test the differences between these two groups for systolic blood pressure, body weight and pulse frequency. What is your conclusion?

Hints

The recoding of dias can be accomplished in various ways. A very quick way is the ifelse function, but it can also be done manually. For the Levenes test, you need to set Highbp as a factor with as.factor().

Exercise 6: Paired continuous data

The data below are from Charles Darwins study of cross- and self-fertilization (Darwin C., 1876: The effect of cross- and self-fertilization in the vegetable kingdom). Pairs of seedlings of the same age, one produced by cross-fertilization and the other by self-fertilization, were grown together so that the members of each pair were reared under nearly identical conditions. The aim was to demonstrate the greater vigour of the cross-fertilized plants. The data are the final heights of each plant after a fixed period of time. The dataset is called DARWIN.SAV (see page A9 in the Appendix).

Pair Cross-fertilized Self-fertilized

9 18.3 16.5

11 23.3 16.3
12 21.0 18.0
13 22.1 12.8
14 23.0 15.5
15 12.0 18.0

Question a

Use the function t.test() to perform a Paired Samples t-test. What is the 95% confidence interval for the difference in final height between cross-fertilized and self-fertilized plants? Is this difference statistically significantly different from zero? What is the assumption underlying this analysis? In parts b and c of this exercise we analyse the data with non-parametric methods.

Hints

Add the parameter paired = TRUE to t.test() for a Paired Samples t-test. As for the assumtions of the t-test, look at the distribution below of the final height of cross-fertilized plants.

Code

# load libraries
library(foreign)

# load dataset
Darwin <- read.spss('data/DARWIN.SAV', to.data.frame = TRUE)

# t-test for the difference between cross-fertilized and self-fertilized plants 
t.test(Darwin$FH_CROSS, Darwin$FH_SELF, paired = TRUE)

Output

t.test(Darwin$FH_CROSS, Darwin$FH_SELF, paired = TRUE)
## 
##  Paired t-test
## 
## data:  Darwin$FH_CROSS and Darwin$FH_SELF
## t = 2.1422, df = 14, p-value = 0.05025

## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.003205724  5.216539057
## sample estimates:
## mean of the differences 
##                2.606667

Discussion

There are four assumptions of the paired t-test:

- The dependent variable must be continuous (interval/ratio).
- The observations are independent of one another.
- The dependent variable should be approximately normally distributed.
- The dependent variable should not contain any outliers.

The histogram of the final heights of the cross-fertilized plant shows the data is not normally distributed. Therefore, we use non-parametric methods in question b and c of this exercise.

Exercise 7: Trend Test

The data file BACKPAIN (see page A3) contains data from a trial on the treatment of chronic low back pain. 100 patients were randomized to one out of four treatment groups:

Blockage
Medication
Bupivacaine Bupivacaine_Tramcinolon Total
Nerve root only 25 25 50
Nerve root_Facetoint 24 26 50
Total 49 51 100

Group 3: Bupivacaine + Nerve root_Facetoint;
Group 4: Bupivacaine_Tramcinolon + Nerve root_Facetoint

One of the outcomes analyzed was the hours pain per day (HPD). The maximum score for this outcome was set to 16. It was measured three days before the blockade (T = 0) and 6 weeks after the blockade (T = 1). (In reality the follow-up was longer.)

Question b

Use the appropriate test to check for a difference of the scores at baseline between the four groups.

Hints

As the scores are not normally distributed, we need to use non-parametric tests (i.e.the Kruskal-Wallis Test). With this kind of tests, we can decide whether the population distributions are identical without assuming them to follow the normal distribution. An appropriate test then is the Kruskal-Wallis. Therefore, we can use the kruskal.test() function.

Code

# Performs Kruskal-Wallis accross groups
kruskal.test(HPD0 ~ GROUP, data = Backpain)

Output

# Performs Kruskal-Wallis accross groups
kruskal.test(HPD0 ~ GROUP, data = Backpain) 
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  HPD0 by GROUP
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 2.972, df = 3, p-value = 0.396

Discussion

The null hypothesis is There is no difference in HGD0 across groups. The p-value is 0.396, therefore, we do not reject the null hypothesis i.e.there is no significant difference in HGD0 across the groups. This is in line with the visual inspection under question a.

    Question b

    How many people have high blood pressure? Express this value as a proportion. Verify whether the sample mean is indeed the same as the sample prevalence of high blood pressure. Now get a confidence interval for the prevalence of high blood pressure. Remark: This confidence interval can be calculated based on different distributions. In this case, we will calculate it based on the standard normal distribution, as our sample size is large.

    Hints

  • For the first part lets use functions table() and prop.table().
  • The calculation of the confidence interval can be a bit tricky. Remember how you define the confidence interval of a proportion (p) based on a normal distribution: \(95\% CI = p \pm 1.96 \sqrt\frac{p(1-p)} {N}\)

    • Code

    # number of individuals with normal and high BP 
table(BLDPRES$highbp)

# now the same indices but in percentages 
prop.table(table(BLDPRES$highbp))

# compare with the mean of the variable
mean(BLDPRES$highbp)

# Lets use now the normal distribution to calculate the Z statistic (this number is very used in statistics so you can even memorize it)
alpha <- 0.05
z <- qnorm(1 - alpha / 2)

# Compute the CI
p <- 0.1402439 # sample prevalence of high blood pressure
N <- 328       # sample size
p + c(-1, 1) * z * sqrt(p * (1 - p) / N)

    Question c

    Now, lets test if the observed trend is statistically significant. In order to do this we will use two different methods: 1) a chi-square test and 2) trend test. Look carefully at the output of both tests. Can you identify what is the difference between these tests? Why is the number of degrees of freedom different? What is your conclusion about the relation?

    In order to see whether this trend test depends on the values attached to the categories of stage (now: 1, 2, 3 and 4), recode these values to: 1, 2, 100, 1000. See what happens with the significance of the test. What is your conclusion?

    Hints

    Use the function prop.test() for the chi-square test, and the prop.trend.test() for the trend test. You can use the combined dataset which you just created at Question b. Note that this last test has the option to change the score flag (you can then recode categories of the STAGE variable).

    Code

    #chi squared test
prop.test(combined$weight_loss, combined$total)

#Trend test with the original score codes
prop.trend.test(combined$weight_loss, combined$total, score = c(1, 2, 3, 4))

#Test wether the trend test depends on the "score" values, recode them.
prop.trend.test(combined$weight_loss, combined$total, score = c(1, 2, 100, 1000))

    Output

    ## 
##  4-sample test for equality of proportions without continuity
##  correction
## 
## data:  combined$weight_loss out of combined$total
## X-squared = 4.4991, df = 3, p-value = 0.2124
## alternative hypothesis: two.sided
## sample estimates:
##    prop 1    prop 2    prop 3    prop 4 
## 0.2162162 0.2871287 0.3043478 0.3787879
    ##

##  using scores: 1 2 3 4

    ## 
##  Chi-squared Test for Trend in Proportions
## 
## data:  combined$weight_loss out of combined$total ,
##  using scores: 1 2 100 1000
## X-squared = 3.2393, df = 1, p-value = 0.07189

    Discussion

    Based on the chi-square results, one will claim there are no significant differences accross the different stages (p = 0.212). However, the trend test with the original scoring of the stages show that there was a significant trend! (p = 0.038), this is because actually the chi-quare compares all groups and thus, you make use of 3 degrees of freedom (\(\chi\)-square test compares 4 groups, so df = 4 - 1 = 3). While in the trend test you are using just one degree of freedom by testing the slope of one line. Therefore, there is a linear trend, but the groups do not differ significantly.

    Changing the codes of the stage categories resulted in a non significant trend (p = 0.072). In other words, if you would now draw a line through the points it will be less steep (slope is smaller), and not significant. This is one of the main critics for the trend tests as they will depend on how you score the categories.

    Code

    n <- dim(schizo_pos)[1]
schizo_pos$DIAGA_code <- ifelse(schizo_pos$DIAGA == "schizophrenia", 1, 0) # code schizophrenia
schizo_pos$DIAGB_code <- ifelse(schizo_pos$DIAGB == "schizophrenia", 1, 0) # code schizophrenia

schizo_pos$DIAGA_code - schizo_pos$DIAGB_code  # print the difference 
m <- mean(schizo_pos$DIAGA_code - schizo_pos$DIAGB_code) # calculate the mean
sd <- sd(schizo_pos$DIAGA_code - schizo_pos$DIAGB_code)  # calculate the standard deviation
se <- sd / sqrt(n) # calculate the standard error 

lower <- m - qt(0.975, n - 1) * se   # the lower bound of the 95%-CI
upper <- m + qt(0.975, n - 1) * se   # the upper bound of the 95%-CI

c(lower, m, upper)

# alternatively, use the t-test
t.test(schizo_pos$DIAGA_code, schizo_pos$DIAGB_code, paired = TRUE)

    Hints

The stanadard error in turn can be calculated se <- sd/sqrt(n). To find the right number from the Student t Distribution you can use the following code qt(0.975, n - 1).

  • Use the \(\chi^2\)-test based on \(\sum\)(Observed-Expected)\(^2/\)Expected.

  • Expected counts are computed by multiplying the total by column and the total by row of a cell and dividing by the overall total. E.g. for the first cell. \(\dfrac{34*15}{65}=7.8\).

  • \(\chi^2= \dfrac{(5-7.8)^2}{7.8}+\dfrac{(29-26.2)^2}{26.2}+\dfrac{(10-7.2)^2}{7.2}+\dfrac{(2.1-23.8)^2}{23.8}=2.73\)

  • Using the \(\chi^2\) table find the row that corresponds to the relevant degrees of freedom (1). \(\chi^2_{0.10}(1)=2.71<2.73<3.84=\chi^2_{0.05}(1)\) therefore \(0.05<p<0.10\).

  • You can use R for the calculations above. You could also use the function chisq.test

    • Output

    aspirin <- read.spss("./data/Aspirin.sav", to.data.frame = TRUE) # load data
chisq.test(aspirin$TREATM, aspirin$HYP, correct = FALSE)
    ## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  aspirin$TREATM and aspirin$HYP
## X-squared = 2.8142, df = 1, p-value = 0.09343

    Discussion

    The null hypothesis is ???The two treatment groups have the same risk of developing hypertension??? versus the alternative hypothesis ???The two treatment groups have different risk of developing hypertension???. As \(p>0.05\) (\(p = 0.09\)) for the two-sided \(\chi^2\)-test, we do not reject the null hypothesis, i.e.there is no significant difference in risk between the two treatment groups. In other words, aspirin is not efficacious in the prevention of hypertension in pregnant women in their third trimester with high risk of pregnancy induced hypertension.

    Hints

    Difference in risk

  • The difference in risk is \(p_1-p_0=\dfrac{5}{34}-\dfrac{10}{31}=-0.176\)

  • The standard error can be calculated as follows: \(se(p_1-p_0)=\sqrt{\dfrac{p_1(1-p_1)}{n_1}+\dfrac{p_0(1-p_0)}{n_0}}=0.104\)

  • The \(95\%\)-CI for the risk difference (RD) is \(RD\pm1.96*se=(-0.380, 0.028)\)

    • Relative risk
  • The relative risk \((RR)\) is \(\dfrac{p_1}{p_0}=\dfrac{\dfrac{5}{34}}{\dfrac{10}{31}} = 0.456\)

  • The \(95\%\)-CI for the relative risk is \(RR*\exp (\pm1.96*\sqrt{\dfrac{1-p_1}{n_1*p_1}+\dfrac{1-p_0}{n_0*p_0}}=(0.175, 1.187)\)

    • Odds Ratio
  • The odds ratio \((OR)\) is \(\dfrac{odds_1}{odds_0}=\dfrac{\dfrac{p_1}{1-p_1}}{\dfrac{p_0}{1-p_0}} = 0.361\)

  • The \(95\%\)-CI for the odds ratio is \(OR*\exp{\pm1.96*\sqrt{\dfrac{1}{5}+\dfrac{1}{29}+\dfrac{1}{10}+\dfrac{1}{21}}}=(0.107, 1.212)\)

  • You can use R for the calculations above. A useful function for a more direct calculation of RR and OR and their \(95%\)-CI is epitab in package epitools

    Exercise 12: Confidence interval for proportion and odds

    In this exercise we do not make use of a data set. All information is given in the text and we will use R as a calculator to solve the exercise.

    In a sample of 300 diabetes patients the prevalence of high blood pressure (defined as diastolic blood pressure > 95 mmHg) was found to be \(\dfrac{18}{300} = 0.06\).

    Question a

    Calculate 90% confidence interval for the prevalence in the population.

    Code

    # Assign values to R objects that will be used for further calculations for this exercise:
n <- 300  # n is the number of diabetes patients
p <- 0.06 # p is the prevalence of high blood pressure in this sample
x <- 18   # x is the number of high blood pressure cases

SE <- sqrt(p * (1 - p) / n) # compute the SE needed for the calculation of the 90% confidence interval (CI)
SE # print the obtained SE

CI.lo <- p - 1.645 * SE  # calculate lower limit of the 90%-CI
CI.up <- p + 1.645 * SE  # calculate upper limit of the 90%-CI
CI.Q1 <- c(CI.lo, CI.up) # assign the lower and upper limit of the CI obtained into a vector
CI.Q1 # print the 90%-CI

    Hints

    Use the equation to calculate the standard error (SE) and the 90% confidence inteval (CI). Remember to use 1.645 when calculating a 90%-CI.

    Output

SE.ln.odds

    Question c

    Calculate a 95% confidence interval for the prevalence. What sample size (N) would be approximately needed if one wants to limit the width of the 95% confidence interval for the prevalence to two times 0.01? (Meaning that the estimate will be within 1 percentage point from the truth.)

    Code

    # 95% CI for the prevalence
lb <- p - 1.96 * sqrt( p * ( 1 - p ) / n)
ub <- p + 1.96 * sqrt( p * ( 1 - p ) / n)
c(lb, ub)
# We can calculate needed sample size using the following formula:
# 1.96 * SE(p) = 0.01
# 1.96 * sqrt( p * ( 1 - p ) / N) = 0.01
N <- (1.96 * sqrt(p * (1 - p)) / 0.01) ^ 2
N
